[[File:The Columbia Condominium.JPG|thumb|The Columbia Residences, formerly known as the Columbia Hospital for Women, in [[Washington, D.C.]]]] The '''Columbia Hospital for Women''' was a [[hospital]] located in [[Washington, D.C.]] Originally opening in 1866 as a health-care facility for wives and [[widow]]s of [[American Civil War|Civil War]] soldiers, it moved in 1870 from [[Thomas Circle]] to its later location at 2425 L Street, [[Northwest, Washington, D.C.|NW]] in the [[West End, Washington, D.C.|West End]] neighborhood. The Columbia became a private, [[non-profit hospital]] when [[President of the United States|President]] [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] signed legislation transferring it to a board of directors in 1953. The facility closed in 2002 and the building was converted into a [[condominium]], '''The Columbia Residences'''.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/hmd/medtour/columbia.html| title=Historic Medical Sites in the Washington, DC Area| author=[[United States National Library of Medicine]]| accessdate=July 16, 2007}}</ref>
Among the more than 250,000 people born at Columbia Hospital for Women were [[Duke Ellington]], [[Al Gore]], [[Katherine Heigl]] and [[Michael Dominic]].
